   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3182_1.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>The Little Orchard</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Shoreham</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Kent</addrLine>
               </address>
               <milestone unit="section" xml:id="m01"/>
               <milestone unit="section" xml:id="m02"/>
               <milestone unit="section" xml:id="m03"/>

               <dateline>
                  <date when="1915-03-31">March 31</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>My dear friend</salute>
            </opener>

            <p>Thank you so much for sending me the enclosed. I feel very strongly as to "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1915_ThePityOfIt">The Pity of it</ref>", regarding the war. For
               there can be no doubt that we &amp; <placeName ref="#pl:Germany"> Germany</placeName>
               have much more in common than we &amp; <placeName ref="#pl:France"
               >France</placeName>, or we &amp; <placeName ref="#pl:Russia">Russia</placeName>. Had
               we been fighting either of them, how these <hi rend="underline">detestable</hi>
               newspapers <choice><abbr>w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</abbr>
                  <expan>would</expan></choice> have screamed about past <add place="above"
                  >French</add> atrocities during the Commune &amp;c &amp; about <pb n="2"
                  facs="uoedh_hl_h.3182_2.jpg"/> Russian "Pogroms". – I wonder, – do the journalists
               remember the favourite poetic effusion about the Russians not getting <placeName
                  ref="#pl:Istanbul">Constantino­ple</placeName> etc. –</p>

            <p>I should <hi rend="underline">very much</hi> like to hear <persName
                  ref="#ps:LordMorley">Lord Morley</persName> &amp; <persName ref="#ps:JohnBurns">
                  John Burns</persName> give their views, <hi rend="underline">privately</hi>. Both
               are men of much greater honesty &amp; finer character than many other members of this
               Cabinet. I suppose they would say that it is a <pb n="3" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3182_3.jpg"
               /> case of choosing the least of two evils, &amp; that it was morally worse to cause
               such misery to their country than to shirk helping <placeName ref="#pl:France"
                  >France</placeName>? – It is a curious point of view, <del>no doubt</del> – but no
               doubt sincere, &amp; in <persName ref="#ps:JohnBurns"> John Burns'</persName> case it
               is almost heroic to give up power and influence – (<choice><abbr>wh.</abbr>
                  <expan>which</expan></choice> must mean so much to him,) as well as money. –</p>
            <p> Ought you not to have put "er <hi rend="underline">soll</hi>" and "Du bist" in the
               poem – or is your spelling intentional – &amp; as the <placeName ref="#pl:Dorset"
                  >Dorset</placeName> people literally pronounce? –</p>
            <p>I can't tell you how <pb n="4" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3182_4.jpg"/> charming I think your
                  "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1870_WhenISetOutForLyonnesse"
                        ><choice><sic>Lyonesse</sic><corr>Lyonnesse</corr></choice></ref>" lyric. I
               must learn it by heart one of these days. –</p>
            <p>I am so sorry that dear <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">Florence</persName> has
               been suffering from sciatica. I had it once for a <hi rend="underline">long</hi>
               time, &amp; then <hi rend="underline">quite</hi> got rid of it, owing to treatment by
               an electric battery on the nerve – Please give my best love to her – I hope she has
               seen some nice &amp; rare birds in your garden. I look eagerly for them here. –</p>
            <p>To return to the War – did you not think it injudicious of <persName
                  ref="#ps:JohnFrench">Sir John F.</persName> to speak with such</p>
            <!-- Could this be John French, 1st Earl of Ypres?-->


            <pb n="5" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3182_5.jpg"/>

            <p xml:id="h3182a" corresp="#m01" style="transform:rotateZ(-90deg)">a confident &amp;
               sanguine tone to reporters?</p>
            <p xml:id="h3182b" corresp="#m02" style="transform:rotateZ(-90deg)">I wonder when you
               think of coming to <placeName ref="#pl:London">London</placeName>? I wish you
                        <choice><abbr>w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</abbr>
                  <expan>would</expan></choice> both come &amp; spend a long day here in the
               orchard?</p>
            <closer xml:id="h3182c" corresp="#m03" style="transform:rotateZ(-90deg)">
               <salute><choice><abbr>Ev</abbr>
                     <expan>Ever</expan></choice>
                  <choice><abbr>yr</abbr>
                     <expan>your</expan></choice>
                  <choice><abbr>affec.</abbr>
                     <expan>affectionate</expan></choice> friend</salute>
               <signed>F. H</signed>
            </closer>



         </div>
